<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="83" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1400,2039]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1400,1426]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Members of the genus are externally quite similar to certain species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1854" box="[1060,1139,1400,1426]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Sesapa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1060,1139,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Sesapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1152,1280,1400,1427]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–16" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[204,1375,186,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[194,1392,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–16. Hampsonascia (9–14) and Sesapa (15–16) spp.: adults. Depositories of the specimens: 9–11, 14 and 16 in MWM/ZSM (11 ex CAV); 12 and 13 in CAV; 15 in NHMUK (©The Trustees of NHMUK)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5656530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5656530/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Figs 15, 16</figureCitation>
; illustrated by Volynkin (2017, 2019) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Wu, S." box="[456,586,1436,1463]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" pagination="75 - 83" refId="ref6325" refString="Wu, S. (2019) Reassessment of the generic definition of Sesapa Walker, 1854, with descriptions of two new species of Taiwan (Erebidae, Arctiinae, Lithosiini). Tinea, 25 (Supplement 1), 75 - 83." type="journal article" year="2019">Wu (2019))</bibRefCitation>
and the differences between genera can be found in genitalia structures. The autapomorphic feature in the male genitalia is an extremely long distal diverticulum of the vesica which is bifurcated in most species (except for 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Černý, 2021" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2021" box="[525,636,1508,1534]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Hampsonascia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aulaca" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[525,636,1508,1534]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">H. aulaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[643,707,1508,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[643,707,1508,1534]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). The similarly elongate diverticulum is also known in the genus 
<emphasis box="[151,296,1544,1570]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Integrivalvia</emphasis>
Volynkin &amp; S.-Y. Huang, 2019 (illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Volynkin, A. V. &amp; Huang, S. - Y. &amp; Ivanova, M. S." box="[824,1083,1544,1570]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" pagination="14 - 92" refId="ref6173" refString="Volynkin, A. V., Huang, S. - Y. &amp; Ivanova, M. S. (2019) An overview of genera and subgenera of the Asura / Miltochrista generic complex (Lepidoptera, Erebidae, Arctiinae). Part 1. Barsine Walker, 1854 sensu lato, Asura Walker, 1854 and related genera, with descriptions of twenty new genera, ten new subgenera and a check list of taxa of the Asura / Miltochrista generic complex. Ecologica Montenegrina, 26, 14 - 92. https: // doi. org / 10.37828 / em. 2019.26.3" type="journal article" year="2019">
Volynkin 
<emphasis box="[934,991,1544,1570]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">et al.</emphasis>
(2019))
</bibRefCitation>
but in the latter it has a curved sclerotized basal plate and is never bifurcated. The valva structure of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2019" box="[954,1120,1581,1606]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Hampsonascia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[954,1120,1581,1606]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Hampsonascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to that of certain groups of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1819" box="[266,404,1616,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[266,404,1616,1642]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Miltochrista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and strongly dissimilar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1854" box="[788,867,1616,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Sesapa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[788,867,1616,1642]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Sesapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[882,1013,1616,1642]" captionStart="FIGURES 31–34" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1736,1760]" captionTargetBox="[164,1432,189,1701]" captionTargetId="figure-21@10.[151,1435,181,1712]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 31–34. Sesapa (31–33) and Longarsine (34) spp.: male genitalia. Depositories of the specimens dissected: 31 and 32 in NHMUK (©The Trustees of NHMUK); 33 in MWM/ZSM; 34 in SCAU (photo by S.-Y. Huang)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5656542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5656542/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Figs 31, 32</figureCitation>
; illustrated by Volynkin (2017; 2019) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Wu, S." box="[198,312,1652,1679]" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" pagination="75 - 83" refId="ref6325" refString="Wu, S. (2019) Reassessment of the generic definition of Sesapa Walker, 1854, with descriptions of two new species of Taiwan (Erebidae, Arctiinae, Lithosiini). Tinea, 25 (Supplement 1), 75 - 83." type="journal article" year="2019">Wu (2019</bibRefCitation>
, partim)) due to the elongate distal section of the costa forming a distal process whereas the costa of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1854" box="[151,230,1688,1714]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Sesapa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,230,1688,1714]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Sesapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is short and terminates in the middle or in the distal two thirds of valva without forming a process (an autapomorphic feature of the genus). Additionally, the juxta of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2019" box="[810,976,1725,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Hampsonascia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[810,976,1725,1750]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Hampsonascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is entirely sclerotized whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1854" box="[1357,1436,1724,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Sesapa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1357,1436,1724,1750]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Sesapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is subdivided into two lateral parts by a very narrow medial longitudinal membranous commissure. The female genitalia of the two genera are similar in the presence of lateral subostial lobes but different in other aspects. The autapomorphic feature of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2019" box="[442,608,1833,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Hampsonascia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[442,608,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Hampsonascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the extremely elongate densely spinulose appendix bursae with a basal section directed anteriorly and a distal section strongly curved inwardly with a tip directed posteriorly, the structure well-fitting the extremely elongate distal diverticulum in males. Unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2019" box="[987,1153,1905,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Hampsonascia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[987,1153,1905,1930]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Hampsonascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the appendix bursae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1854" box="[151,230,1940,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Sesapa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,230,1940,1966]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Sesapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is short and apically membranous and directed posteriorly. Additionally, the ductus bursae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2019" box="[1270,1436,1941,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Hampsonascia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1270,1436,1941,1966]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Hampsonascia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is entirely sclerotized with an anterior end fused with the sclerotized posterior section of the corpus bursae whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1854" box="[180,259,2012,2038]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Sesapa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[180,259,2012,2038]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="83">Sesapa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the anterior section of the corpus bursae is membranous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="84" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,150,213]" pageId="2" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,150,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="84">Distribution</emphasis>
. Species of the genus are known from north-eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[942,1002,151,177]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="84">India</collectingCountry>
, south-western 
<collectingCountry box="[1179,1246,151,177]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="84">China</collectingCountry>
and northern Indochina.
</paragraph>
